ce:section.ce:para:
TEM image shows that the cobalt nanoparticles with yolk-shell structure are distributed on ZSM-5 evenly (Fig. 2a
                        ). The lattice spacing of the shell is about 0.16 nm and that of the yolk is about 0.20 nm, which corresponds to the (220) and (111) [46]lattice planes of CoO and metallic cobalt, respectively. The special structure consisting of an oxide shell and a metallic core is created by oxidation in air after the catalyst has been reduced in a hydrogen atmosphere. It has been demonstrated that CoO has the properties of semiconductor and the heterojunction structure CoO/Co exhibited photocatalytic activity in hydrogen evolution reaction[47–52]. Indeed, the catalyst Co/ZSM-5 has obvious transient photocurrent responses (Fig. 3a
                        ), demonstrating its ability to generate photo-generated charge carriers under light irradiation [53,54]. Besides, the negative slope of Mott-Schottky plot of Co/ZSM-5 indicates that Co/ZSM-5 is a kind of p-type semiconductor catalyst (Fig. 3b)[55]. Therefore, the catalyst Co/ZSM-5 showed excellent photothermocatalytic activity in the reforming of cellulose to syngas. After Co/ZSM-5 was used in one run in the photothermocatalytic process, the cobalt nanoparticles were coated by graphitic carbon and some carbon nanotube can be observed in its TEM images (Fig. S5). We deduce that the hydrocarbons (such as methane, ethane and other C2+ hydrocarbons) generated from reforming reaction functioned as carbon source and cobalt nanoparticles served as catalyst producing carbon nanotubes. The encapsulated cobalt nanoparticles cannot be oxidized easily, so that there is no yolk-shell structure in the spent Co/ZSM-5. The phase structure of cobalt components in Co/ZSM-5 and spent Co/ZSM-5 can further be confirmed by XRD characterizations (Fig. 2b). In addition to the characteristic diffraction peaks of ZSM-5, two very weak peaks at 57.3° and 44.2° can be distinguished in the XRD patterns of Co/ZSM-5 and spent Co/ZSM-5, corresponding to the (220) lattice diffraction of CoO (PDF#42–1300) and the (111) lattice diffraction of metal cobalt (PDF#15–0806). In XPS analysis(Fig. 2c), the binding energies at 797 eV and 781.7 eV belong to the 2p3/2 and 2p1/2 of CoO[56] in the spectrum of Co/ZSM-5. No metallic cobalt can be deconvolved due to the presence of oxide shell. After reaction or recycling runs, the metallic cobalt can be detected by XPS obviously. It can be deduced that the carbon deposit on catalyst during the reaction can reduce cobalt oxide to metallic cobalt via carbothermal reduction process. The presence of carbon deposit or carbon nanotubes improves the oxidation resistance of catalyst. This special structure of catalyst can even enhance the catalytic activity, explaining the photothermocatalytic performance in the recycling experiments (Fig. 1e).
